==Chinese==
{{zh-forms|s=贞|alt=鼑,𠨀,𣦵,𭾛}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} - a [[ding#Etymology 3|ding]] (oracle bone script [[File:貞-oracle.svg|30px|class=skin-invert]], [[File:貞-oracle-2.svg|30px|class=skin-invert]]; same as {{och-l|鼎}}). Borrowed phonetically for “to divine”; however, bronze tripods in ancient China were sometimes used during rituals. Later, a new character was created by adding {{zh-l|*卜|to divine}} as a radical, hence a semantic component, thus getting {{zh-l|*鼑}} (oracle bone script [[File:貞-oracle-3.svg|30px|class=skin-invert]]; bronze script [[File:貞-bronze.svg|30px|class=skin-invert]]. The bottom component was stylized into the unrelated {{zh-l|*貝}} during the Warring States. Compare {{zh-l|*𠟭}} > {{zh-l|*則}}.

===Etymology===
Various comparisons have been proposed. Within Chinese, it has been compared to {{och-l|偵|id=2|to test; to detect}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), {{och-l|正|id=2|correct; right}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart and Ma, 2020}}). Outside of Chinese, it has been compared to {{cog|bo|དྲང་པོ||straight}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 2020b}}).

